tacitos consumere: Burman's correction, to which the ms. seems to point. For consumere cf. Cic. Phil. 2. 64 Consumptis enim lacrimis tamen in·

quod pudor neqavit: i. e. the comfort of the free expression of her feel- ings‚ cf. 6 and 22—3. Pudor at first kept her from making any appeal; now dolor does not allow her the solace of keeping her suffering to her- sels.

culpa: nominative; literally “whose fault has made,” etc. The word refers to Dido’s love, which restrains her from doing Aeneas any harm. The expression is thus interpreted by Wernsdorf: “Miseram me, quae mea culpa honestum hospitii et coniugii foedus cum Aenea feci, cuius fide nunc impedior quominus nefas aliquod in eum cogitare et me ul· cisci possim.''
